alternatives.transcript: the year was 1612 the five-year-old settlement of Jamestown Virginia was still suffering from the aftermath of desperate years called The Starving time failure to find a crop or product for export had left the colony destitute Indian attacks starvation and disease had cut the population drastically the settlements pharmacist compounding an endless string of ancient nostrums was a little help the Outlook was bleak

new member of the economy was both imaginative and stubborn John Ross with the captive Indian princess Pocahontas who would become his bride had somehow obtained the seeds of the type of tobacco far superior to that grown by the Indians Ralph bought such tobacco might be saleable in London so he said about raising a crop he could hardly have suspected that in doing so he was planting the seeds of a great nation Pocahontas knowledge of Indian Tobacco must have been invaluable in bringing his crops to harvest

in due time after much pruning and cultivation the tobacco leaves were picked and readied for curing after which gathered into bundles called hands they were tenderly packed away for shipment back to England one wonders if John Ross could smell the success The Venture would bring

any shipment as it was rolled out of The Stockade and down to the Waterfront with a mixture perhaps of skepticism and hope transferred to a Longboat the tobacco together with such other meager items has pitched our and wood ashes for soap were carried to the sailing ship Elizabeth anchored out in the James River investors and the Virginia Company which had financed the settlement of Jamestown

I had envisioned an early return on their investment through the discovery of gold it is not hard to guess what their reaction must have been when they received instead barrels of ashes and the leaves of a new type of tobacco but this tiny cargo of Virginia tobacco as we know now was to prove more significant than the discovery of gold for it was the product that would give England its first permanent overseas foothold anywhere in the world and would lead eventually to the development of the North American continent and of the British Empire

the ship gets underway in stands down the James heading for the open ocean with London three to six weeks away depending on wind current and seamanship three months later the happy news came back the new type of tobacco had been most enthusiastically received England would take at a good price as much as could be produced the London company opened its purse strings

before the settlers upon whom it had been about ready to turn its back in addition to needed supplies livestock guns ammunition there were Fabrics in Goods for the women of Jamestown who were giving the colony stability and permanence almost immediately it became apparent that as a direct consequence of Rob's experimental planting the struggling colony had been saved it showed that English development of the new world was possible despite the wide ocean unfriendly Indians and the Hostile Spanish

what's tobacco growing everywhere even in the streets Ralph and Pocahontas were married the first marriage between an Englishman and a Native American this event opened a new era in the settlers relations with the Indians today John Ross tiny crop has grown into a major industry which provides income to some 17 million Americans a seven and a half billion dollar industry that yields annual taxes of more than 3 billion dollars

as Americans celebrate the 350th anniversary of Ralph's crop which marked the start of US foreign trade and commerce we realized that this was truly a remarkable couple from whom many famous Americans have been proud to trace their ancestry their contributions to history were greater perhaps than those of some of their contemporaries who occupy a
